Methodology: High-Throughput Statistical Filtering of Metabolomics Data"To identify statistically robust metabolic biomarkers from our dataset of 154 alkaloids across 8 experimental groups (3 biological replicates per group), we implemented a high-throughput, two-track data analysis pipeline in R. Running individual comparative tests sequentially introduces a profound risk of Type I statistical errors (false positives); therefore, uniform automation and multi-testing corrections were mandatory.

Track 1 (Descriptive Metrics & Visualization): For each of the 154 metabolites, raw data points were grouped by experimental condition to compute group-specific arithmetic Means, Standard Deviations (SD), and Standard Errors of the Mean (SEM). These values establish the foundational baseline for downstream data visualization (e.g., error-barred bar charts and profiles) and descriptive profiling.

Track 2 (Raw Statistical Modeling & Multi-Testing Correction): Concurrently, rather than performing statistics on aggregated group averages—which artificially collapses statistical power and eliminates degrees of freedom—all 24 individual raw replicate values per metabolite were fed directly into an analysis of variance (One-Way ANOVA) framework (Expression ~ Group). This allowed the model to correctly partition within-group technical/biological variance against between-group experimental variance.

To counteract the severe multi-testing problem inherent to analyzing 154 independent ANOVA models simultaneously (where random chance alone guarantees false discoveries), the Benjamini-Hochberg False Discovery Rate (FDR) correction was systematically applied to all raw \(P\)-values. Metabolites yielding an FDR-adjusted \(P\)-value \(<0.05\) were retained as genuinely significant biological responders. For these verified targets, a post-hoc Tukey’s Honest Significant Difference (HSD) test was performed to isolate exact, pairwise group variations (e.g., assessing specific shifts driven by graft combinations or whitefly treatment).

Ultimately, this stringent statistical filter successfully pruned experimental noise and narrowed our expansive alkaloid profile down to a highly reliable, high-confidence subset of changing metabolites. This optimized subset provides the exact, statistically sound foundation required for valid downstream multi-omics integrations, specifically for cross-correlation modeling against mobile genes and Differentially Expressed Genes (DEGs)."

3 Key Talking Points for Your Discussion TomorrowIf your Postdoc asks quick questions, memorize these three short answers:

Why didn't you just use GraphPad Prism?"
Prism requires manually clicking and generating 154 separate data tables and 154 separate ANOVA scripts, which is highly inefficient, prone to human error, and lacks a built-in way to easily apply a global FDR correction across the entire project.

"Why didn't you run the ANOVA on the averages/means?"
If we average the replicates first, the software thinks our sample size is \(n=1\) per group. We have to feed the raw replicates into the ANOVA so the code can accurately calculate the variation within the groups.

"What is the purpose of the Benjamini-Hochberg (BH/FDR) correction?"
When you run 154 tests at a standard \(\alpha = 0.05\), you are mathematically guaranteed to get about 7 or 8 completely fake 'significant' results just by pure random chance. The FDR correction recalculates the \(P\)-values to eliminate those false positives so our final list is 100% real."








"So, here is exactly what I did with the alkaloid data and why it’s the best way to handle it. Instead of doing everything manually, I set up a two-track pipeline in R to process all 154 metabolites at the exact same time. Track one calculates the mean, SD, and SEM for our graphs, while track two handles the actual statistics using the raw replicate data.The main reason we cannot just average the replicates before running the ANOVA is that it completely breaks the math. If we feed group averages into an ANOVA, the software treats our sample size as \(n=1\) instead of \(n=3\). Because a sample size of one has zero variation, the software can't calculate degrees of freedom and the test fails. We have to feed all 24 raw replicate data points directly into the ANOVA so the model can actually measure the background noise within each group and compare it to the real differences between our treatments.Also, since we are testing 154 different metabolites all at once, running standard ANOVAs introduces a massive false-positive problem. By pure random chance, a standard \(p < 0.05\) threshold would give us around 7 or 8 totally fake 'significant' results. To fix this and make sure our data is publication-ready, I applied a Benjamini-Hochberg False Discovery Rate (FDR) correction. This adjusts our \(p\)-values so that any alkaloid left with an adjusted \(p < 0.05\) is a guaranteed, true biological responder. This leaves us with a perfectly narrowed-down, clean list of metabolites that we can confidently pass on to correlate with our mobile genes and DEGs without wasting time on random noise."




"Statistical profiling of the 154 identified alkaloids across the 8 experimental groups was conducted using a parallel-track automated workflow in R. Descriptive statistics, including group means, standard deviations (SD), and standard errors of the mean (SEM), were compiled for data visualization purposes. To preserve statistical power and accurately account for within-group variance, standard One-Way Analysis of Variance (ANOVA) models were fitted utilizing all 24 individual raw replicate values rather than aggregated group means. To control the inflated risk of Type I errors associated with performing 154 simultaneous statistical tests, raw \(P\)-values were rigorously adjusted using the Benjamini-Hochberg False Discovery Rate (FDR) correction. Alkaloids yielding an FDR-corrected \(P\)-value \(<0.05\) were considered statistically significant and subjected to a post-hoc Tukey’s Honest Significant Difference (HSD) test to identify explicit pairwise group alterations. This stringent screening workflow isolated a high-confidence subset of changing metabolites for downstream multi-omics integration and correlation with mobile genes and differentially expressed genes (DEGs)."








# ==============================================================================
# METABOLOMICS TWO-TRACK ANALYSIS: GRAPH PREP & RAW ANOVA WITH FDR
# Alkaloids - 154 metabolites
# ==============================================================================

# Load libraries
library(tidyr)
library(dplyr)

# ------------------------------------------------------------------------------
# STEP 1: Load your data
# ------------------------------------------------------------------------------
raw_data <- read.csv("Alkaloids_rep.csv", 
                     row.names = 1, 
                     check.names = FALSE)

cat("Total metabolites loaded:", nrow(raw_data), "\n")
cat("Total columns loaded:", ncol(raw_data), "\n")
cat("Column names:", colnames(raw_data), "\n")

# ------------------------------------------------------------------------------
# STEP 2: Define groups in YOUR exact column order
# ------------------------------------------------------------------------------
unique_groups <- c("UG", "SS", "LG30", "MM30",
                   "UGWF", "SSWF", "LG30WF", "MM30WF")

group_factor <- factor(c(
  rep("UG",     3),   # UG-1,    UG-2,    UG-3
  rep("SS",     3),   # SS-1,    SS-2,    SS-3
  rep("LG30",   3),   # LG30-1,  LG30-2,  LG30-3
  rep("MM30",   3),   # MM30-1,  MM30-2,  MM30-3
  rep("UGWF",   3),   # UGWF-1,  UGWF-2,  UGWF-3
  rep("SSWF",   3),   # SSWF-1,  SSWF-2,  SSWF-3
  rep("LG30WF", 3),   # LG30WF-1,LG30WF-2,LG30WF-3
  rep("MM30WF", 3)),  # MM30WF-1,MM30WF-2,MM30WF-3
  levels = unique_groups   # forces YOUR order not alphabetical
)

num_metabolites <- nrow(raw_data)

# ------------------------------------------------------------------------------
# STEP 3: Initialize empty matrices for Track 1 (Graphing)
# ------------------------------------------------------------------------------
mean_matrix <- matrix(NA, nrow = num_metabolites, ncol = 8,
                      dimnames = list(rownames(raw_data), unique_groups))
sd_matrix   <- matrix(NA, nrow = num_metabolites, ncol = 8,
                      dimnames = list(rownames(raw_data), unique_groups))
sem_matrix  <- matrix(NA, nrow = num_metabolites, ncol = 8,
                      dimnames = list(rownames(raw_data), unique_groups))

# Initialize vectors for Track 2 (Statistics)
raw_anova_p_values      <- c()
tukey_significant_pairs <- c()

# ==============================================================================
# STEP 4: MAIN LOOP - Run both tracks for all 154 metabolites
# ==============================================================================
for (i in 1:num_metabolites) {
  
  metabolite_name <- rownames(raw_data)[i]
  row_values      <- as.numeric(raw_data[i, ])
  
  # Pair raw values with group labels
  df <- data.frame(
    Intensity = row_values,
    Group     = group_factor
  )
  
  # ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
  # TRACK 1: Mean, SD, SEM per group (for graphs and figures)
  # ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
  for (g in unique_groups) {
    group_data <- df$Intensity[df$Group == g]
    mean_matrix[metabolite_name, g] <- mean(group_data, na.rm = TRUE)
    sd_matrix[metabolite_name, g]   <- sd(group_data,   na.rm = TRUE)
    sem_matrix[metabolite_name, g]  <- sd(group_data,   na.rm = TRUE) / 
      sqrt(sum(!is.na(group_data)))
  }
  
  # ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
  # TRACK 2: One-Way ANOVA on RAW replicate data (NOT averaged)
  # ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
  anova_model   <- aov(Intensity ~ Group, data = df)
  anova_summary <- summary(anova_model)
  
  # Extract raw p-value
  raw_p <- anova_summary[[1]][["Pr(>F)"]][1]
  raw_anova_p_values[metabolite_name] <- raw_p
  
  # Tukey Post-Hoc - tells which specific groups differ
  tukey_res  <- TukeyHSD(anova_model)$Group
  sig_pairs  <- rownames(tukey_res)[tukey_res[, "p adj"] < 0.05]
  
  if (length(sig_pairs) > 0) {
    tukey_significant_pairs[metabolite_name] <- paste(sig_pairs, collapse = "; ")
  } else {
    tukey_significant_pairs[metabolite_name] <- "No specific pair differences"
  }
}

# ------------------------------------------------------------------------------
# STEP 5: Apply FDR/BH correction to all p-values
# ------------------------------------------------------------------------------
fdr_p_values <- p.adjust(raw_anova_p_values, method = "BH")

# ==============================================================================
# STEP 6: Build master results table
# ==============================================================================
colnames(mean_matrix) <- paste0(unique_groups, "_Mean")
colnames(sd_matrix)   <- paste0(unique_groups, "_SD")
colnames(sem_matrix)  <- paste0(unique_groups, "_SEM")

master_results <- data.frame(
  Metabolite        = rownames(raw_data),
  mean_matrix,
  sd_matrix,
  sem_matrix,
  Raw_Anova_P       = raw_anova_p_values,
  FDR_Corrected_P   = fdr_p_values,
  Significant_Pairs = tukey_significant_pairs,
  check.names       = FALSE
)

# ------------------------------------------------------------------------------
# STEP 7: Filter only significant metabolites (FDR < 0.05)
# ------------------------------------------------------------------------------
narrowed_results <- subset(master_results, FDR_Corrected_P < 0.05)

# ==============================================================================
# STEP 8: Save both files
# ==============================================================================
write.csv(master_results,   
          "Alkaloids_all_results.csv",        
          row.names = FALSE)

write.csv(narrowed_results, 
          "Alkaloids_significant_only.csv",   
          row.names = FALSE)

# Print summary
cat("\n✅ Analysis Complete!\n")
cat("Total alkaloids tested:           ", num_metabolites, "\n")
cat("Significant after FDR correction: ", nrow(narrowed_results), "\n")
cat("\nFiles saved:\n")
cat("1. Alkaloids_all_results.csv\n")
cat("2. Alkaloids_significant_only.csv\n")












GUIDE: How to Read and Interpret Our Metabolomics Statistical 

Results1. The Descriptive Basics (The First 24 Columns)The _Mean, _SD, and _SEM columns are calculated using the 3 raw biological replicates for each of the 8 groups. The Mean gives us the absolute baseline level of the metabolite in that specific condition. The SD (Standard Deviation) tells us if our 3 replicates were tightly clustered or wildly inconsistent. The SEM (Standard Error) is the ultimate metric for reliability—this is the exact number we plug in for the error bars on our final publication graphs.

2. The Initial Screen (Raw_Anova_Fdr Column)This is our standard One-Way ANOVA p-value. It looks at all 24 raw replicate data points across all 8 groups simultaneously. If this value is less than 0.05, it acts as a "global flag" telling us: "Hey, this metabolite is changing significantly somewhere among your 8 groups!" However, this column by itself cannot tell us which specific group caused the change, and it doesn't account for false positives yet.

3. The Ultimate Filter (Corre_P Column)This is our Benjamini-Hochberg (BH/FDR) adjusted p-value, and it is the most critical column in the entire project. Because we tested many metabolites all at once, pure random chance guarantees that several standard ANOVA p-values would be false positives. The Corre_P column punishes and corrects the p-values. If a metabolite still has a Corre_P value under 0.05, it means it successfully survived the multi-testing correction. This is our definitive proof that the metabolite is a real biological responder, making it 100% ready for publication.

4. The Target Locator (Significant_Pairs Column)This column contains the results of our Post-Hoc Tukey HSD test, which is our favorite part of the analysis. Instead of making us guess or check all 28 possible group pairs manually, the script automatically lists only the pairs that are truly, significantly different from each other (where the pair's specific adjusted p-value is < 0.05). If a pair is listed (like MM30-UG), the difference between those two groups is scientifically real. If a group combination is missing from this text string, it means their differences are just background noise and should be ignored.
